1270","1180":"1180","1217":"1217","1205":"1205","1216":"1216","1215":"1215","1226":"1226","1224":"1224","1179":"1179","1211":"1211","1 January 1211":"1 January 1211","1218":"1218","Wincanton, Somerset, England":"Wincanton, Somerset, England","Shepton Montague, Somerset, England":"Shepton Montague, Somerset, England","Wycombe Marsh, Buckinghamshire, England":"Wycombe Marsh, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Montague","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from either Montaigu-le-bois (Manche) or Montaigu (Manche, Aisne), named with Old French <i>mont</i> ‘hill’ + <i>agu</i> ‘pointed’ (from Latin <i>acutus</i>). Drogo de Montagud was a companion of William the Conqueror and founder of the <b>Montagu(e)</b> family, among whom the personal name <i>Drogo</i> was revived in the 19th century. Another family of the name <b>Monatgu</b> have held the titles of Duke of Montagu, Earl of Sandwich, Earl and Duke of Manchester, Earl of Halifax, and Earl of Beaulieu, and.","Irish: adopted as equivalent of Gaelic <b>Mac Taidhg</b> (see   McTigue  )."],"variants":[{"name":"McTigue","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Taidhg</b>, ‘son of <i>Tadhg</i>’, a personal name originally meaning ‘poet’ or ‘philosopher’. Compare   McCaig  ."]}]},{"name":"Drew","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["short form of   Andrew  , often used as an independent given name in Scotland, and in recent years increasingly popular elsewhere in the English-speaking world, also as a girl's name, borne for example by the American actress  Drew Barrymore  (  b. 1975 )."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":32,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Drew de Montague was born in 1183, in Shepton Montague, Somerset, England, his father, William de Montague, was 24 and his mother, Isabel of Somerset, was 22. He married Alice de Basset in 1205, in Wycombe Marsh, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1216, in his hometown, at the age of 33."},"et":{"1183–1216":"1183–1216","1180–1226":"1180–1226","1187–1217":"1187–1217","1180–1224":"1180–1224","1211–1270":"1211–1270","1160–1217":"1160–1217","1161–1218":"1161–1218","1187":"1187","1183":"1183","1161":"1161","1160":"1160","1270":"1270","1180":"1180","1217":"1217","1205":"1205","1216":"1216","1215":"1215","1226":"1226","1224":"1224","1179":"1179","1211":"1211","1 January 1211":"1. jaanuar 1211","1218":"1218","Wincanton, Somerset, England":"Wincanton, Somerset, England","Sh